@ssigwart Thanks for the report, I can see the issue is that we're trimming the entries being imported into `restricted-upload.data`.

@coreruleset/core-developers Does anyone know why we trim the entries in `restricted-upload.data` when importing them from `restricted-files.data`, and `lfi-os-files.data`? For instance with `/proc/mtrr` we're shortening it to just `mtrr` which increases the chances of false positives.
The idea is to prevent files with these names from being uploaded at all, since an attacker might be able to move them later or otherwise obfuscate the path. For example, if we matched `proc/mtrr`, a file named `mtrr` could still be uploaded. That being said, paths like `.boto` don't have a prefix in `restricted-files.data` either.

I think the bigger issue is the way we use `@pmFromFile` there, as it produceds substring matches, which isn't what we want, IMO.
@theseion

> I think the bigger issue is the way we use @pmFromFile there, as it produceds substring matches, which isn't what we want, IMO.

Agreed, but how do you suggest fixing the way we use the `@pmFromFile` operator to prevent false positives like this? Unless I'm missing something, the boundary provided by that operator won't work for this case. The only other solution is to switch to a regex which iirc is heavier than the `@pmFromFile` operator.
Absolutely. One thing, which we've done before, I believe, could be to add a chain rule that runs the more precise regex only when `@pmFromFile` found a match in the first place. The chain rule could then also use a macro for the match found in the start rule, so we would't have to create a regex that can match every entry, e.g., `@rx %{MATCH_DATA}\b`. Of course, using a macro would require the regex to be compiled for each run, but as runs should be less frequent, maybe it could work.

